== '''Dois I. Rosser Jr.''' ==

Dois Rosser has a longtime career as a businessman in Hampton Roads birthed multiple auto dealerships, land development projects and numerous business ventures.  As he will quickly say, “all of my life in the business world was preparation for what God has for me now.”  As Dois sat at the feet of Pastor Dick Woodward in the late seventies, hearing Dick’s fresh approach to the scriptures, he became burdened to get the Word into the world.  He embarked on a project recording Pastor Woodward’s [http://www.minibiblecollege.org/ Mini Bible College].  This message was first broadcast in America, then throughout Central and South America, and is now translated in 26 languages spoken by over 4 billion people.  During a trip to India in 1986, Dois saw the immense need for providing solid places of worship for congregations whereby they could be nurtured in their faith.  This led him to build ICM’s first two churches.  Since then, over 2,900 churches are built or under construction in 48 countries throughout the world.

Dois currently serves as the chair emeritus and founder of [http://www.icm.org/ International Cooperating Ministries].  He previously served on the board of Trans World Radio, the Lausanne Conference for World Evangelism, and Leighton Ford Ministries, Youth Focus, Overseas Council for Theological & Missions, Inc., and Prison Fellowship Ministries.  Time magazine awarded him its Virginia Quality Dealer Award in 2000; in 1989 he was elected Layman of the Year by the Religious Heritage of America.  In 1988 he received a National Brotherhood and Sisterhood citation from the National Conference of Christians and Jews.  In 1986 he was presented the Unsung Virginia award for his quiet contributions to his home community.  Dois was educated at the Walton School of Commerce in Chicago.  He lives in Hampton, Virginia, and has been married to the former Shirley Sutton since 1943.  They have three daughters, 2 sons in law and eight grandchildren and 3 great grandchildren.

