'''Panmure House''' was a country house in [[Monikie]], [[Angus]], [[Scotland]]. It was the seat of the [[Earl of Panmure]].
Panmure House was designed by the king's master mason [[John Mylne (1611-1667)|John Mylne]], although he died in 1667, before it was completed. The client was George Maule, 3rd Earl of Panmure (1650–1686). On Mylne's death, the work was continued by Alexander Nisbet, an Edinburgh mason, and the interior was fitted out by James Bain, the king's wright. Sir [[William Bruce (architect)|William Bruce]] was sometimes credited with the design in the past, and he did apparently advise the earl after Mylne's death, but he only designed the gates and gate piers.<ref name=Gow>Gow, pp.52–58</ref> After the death of the 3rd Earl, his son [[James Maule, 4th Earl of Panmure|James]], now 4th Earl, added the wings. In the 19th century, the house was extended by [[David Bryce]] in the [[Scottish Baronial style]]. The house was demolished in the 1950s.<ref name=Gow/>
